        <section id="homeostasis" class="mb-16 pt-16 -mt-16">
            <h2 class="section-title">The Theory of Homeostasis</h2>
            <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-xl text-lg text-slate-700 space-y-4">
                <p>Psyphibiotriadics expands the traditional concept of homeostasis. It's not just about maintaining physiological stability, but achieving an optimal and dynamic balance and harmonious functioning across all three Triadic Pillars: the Psychological Mind, the Physical Brain and Body, and the Philosophical Energies.</p>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-sky-700 mt-4">Key Concepts:</h4>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Dynamic Equilibrium:</strong> The pillars are in continuous exchange, driving constant movement along a spectrum of well-being.</li>
                    <li><strong>Spectrum, Not a Fixed Point:</strong> The optimal human condition is a dynamic range of balance across multiple parameters, not a single ideal state.</li>
                    <li><strong>Non-Linear Relationships:</strong> Small changes in one area can produce disproportionately large or small effects in others, highlighting the system's complexity.</li>
                    <li><strong>Individual Variation:</strong> "Optimal" varies significantly due to genetics, environment, lifestyle, and values. Research aims to map spectra of possible states and identify factors for movement along them.</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-4">This refined understanding necessitates complex systems thinking and personalized approaches to guide individuals towards their unique optimal states of well-being.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="research" class="mb-16 pt-16 -mt-16">
            <h2 class="section-title">Research & Assessment</h2>
            <p class="text-center text-slate-600 mb-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto">To validate its framework, Psyphibiotriadics employs diverse research methodologies and comprehensive assessment tools. This section highlights the approaches used to study the Triadic Pillars and their interactions.</p>
            
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-12">
                <div class="card">
                    <h3 class="card-title">Research Methodologies</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">A multi-faceted approach is essential:</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Quantitative:</strong> Physiological data (EEG, ECG, GSR), statistical analysis, controlled experiments.</li>
                        <li><strong>Qualitative:</strong> Phenomenological interviews, thematic analysis, narrative analysis to explore subjective experiences.</li>
                        <li><strong>Mixed Methods:</strong> Combining quantitative and qualitative data for comprehensive understanding (e.g., sequential exploratory or convergent parallel designs).</li>
                        <li><strong>Longitudinal Studies:</strong> Tracking individuals over time to understand dynamic processes.</li>
                        <li><strong>Case Studies:</strong> In-depth analysis of individual cases for unique insights.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3 class="card-title">Integrated Assessment Approaches</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">Bridging objective and subjective data:</p>
                     <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Multimodal Data Fusion:</strong> Combining self-reports, physiological measures, and behavioral observations. AI/ML helps identify patterns.</li>
                        <li><strong>Neurophenomenology:</strong> Integrating first-person accounts with neuroscientific data to study consciousness and subjective states rigorously.</li>
                        <li><strong>Sensory Perception:</strong> Using sensory experiences (touch, smell, sound, sight) as data points reflecting the interplay of the Triadic Pillars.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="card mb-12">
